Takeaway from #AOS2020 working group 4: "Maximizing the benefit of data technologies requires that the #ArcticData community work closely with the broader community to address focused, real-world problems that are important to #Arctic residents and #IndigenousPeoples."

"There needs to be a very solid bridge between the #scientists and the #policymakers in order for initiatives to be pushed through" - if scientists are clear about their priorities and good about communicating them, #progress will be made. #AOS2020

That "protocol" - everyone on the call discusses, then writes for 10 minutes, then discusses, then writes, etc until the document is in a good place. #virtualwaysofworking

Another perspective - what will #Arctic #socialscientists do? Can they conduct #interviews virtually? Will this lead to a shift in how their #fieldwork will be done? Peter Pulsifer cautions: his research was halted out of #respect for the communities dealing with the #pandemic.

@PopePolar asking an interesting question in #AOS2020 #workinggroup4 - do we think perceptions of #datareuse will be changing as #Arctic #fieldwork this summer gets cancelled? Will #researchers access and analyze more "old" #data now that they're not going into the field?

#AOS2020 #workinggroup4 discussing the need for #data and #communityengagement training among #earlycareer researchers - I was happy to inform them that training opportunities do exist from the @arcticdatactr! https://t.co/2uFJgeaegT

Competing perspectives on this discussion - the #data community should engage with decision makers and local #stakeholders in the #Arctic (and make sure #indigenouspeoples have a seat at the table), but #funding for that often isn't there. #AOS2020

Another early morning (2:30 am Pacific!) to talk about #communitybuilding and #datainteroperability. Ruth Duerr of @roninin & @ESIPfed discussing the need for #metadata validators and actually persistent identifiers for #FAIRdata in repositories.
